  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "JbVHLsMm0QOenSS7LtfGiKGPBdI=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:42.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## What `RedundancyLevel` does NOT solve\n\nRedundancy is a READ-side feature: erasure-coded parity lets a downloader RACE-fetch from multiple neighbourhood peers when the primary chunk is missing or slow. It assumes the chunk has already been pushed out.\n\n**It does not fix:**\n\n1. **Bee push-sync latency from sender to target neighborhood.** This is the dominant component of the ~10s GSOC-ping floor on collab ops. Redundancy runs after push-sync completes \u2014 it cannot shorten it.\n\n2. **Feed-head discoverability.** The \"receiver serves stale profile\" problem on 2.7.x is about *feed-index lookup* returning an old update, not about the payload chunk being unavailable. `RedundancyLevel` applies to the chunk pointed to by a feed update, not to the index walk that locates the latest update.\n\nSo it is the right tool for bounding read tail latency on already-propagated data, but not for the feed-staleness or push-sync problems we also see.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:42.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:42.000Z"
    }
  },
